Several 'British Requests' did reach service, including the Mustang,
Havoc, Martin's Maryland and Baltimore.
Spitfire with producibility changes comes immediately to mind. A
simpler main wing spar and more fuel are obvious changes. IMHO this
would have superseded the Mustang. This might have caused Curtiss to
make Spits which would have been a much greater contribution than
hordes of P40s. Packard did make a lot of Merlins, too.
Since BE had no viable day bombers the US would have made their own.
Same goes for trainers, cargo, carrier and patrol planes.
Mosquito, maybe. Closest equivalent we had was probably the B26. But
US had little experience in plywood aircraft construction and lacked
the 'farm club' of woodcrafters. Yes, we had one (1) plywood twin-
engine trainer and the gliders, but only due to the relative dearth of
aluminum.
