Interesting question, which I mostly &quot;answer&quot; with more questions...

I'd venture that a notional production-handicapped US would have done
well to concentrate on  what it did unequivocally better than any
others: tactical naval aircraft with the range and durability for
carrier operations (at least one type of multirole fighter and one
type each of both dive and torpedo bombers); a heavy bomber suitable
for ETO daylight operations (B-24 if we can figure out how to produce
it -- maybe the baroque manner in which it was manufactured, like an
early false start on Airbus, could have been streamlined); an escort
for it (the P-51 gets the nod there, able to do the job of the others
at less cost in resources); and the  B-29.     Making room for the
C-46, C-47, and the best of the mediums (say a B-26, hopefully with an
improved wing earlier) might have been a good idea for the ETO as
well.

This assumes that in the alternate history we are able to achieve
quality and innovation as we did, but for whatever reason are unable
to achieve the production volume.  (The agility and effectiveness with
which the US economy was put onto a war footing was itself a
remarkable achievement and a great contribution to the Allied effort,
though attributing victory to it is an all too common sophistry.  If
it hadn't succeeded, you end up with a different war.)    If instead
you mean that we prove unable to produce satisfactory front-line
aircraft at all and must import them, things get a lot logistically
messier, especially if it leaves us without a bomber that can carry
enough weight for enough distance, survivably, to deliver the A-bomb.
It becomes hard to figure out how to conduct the  Pacific campaigns as
well (especially the island hopping one)  without more or less the
number and kind of planes that we had there -- not only for attack,
but force protection and interdiction of Japanese logistics and
reinforcement.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; For the purposes of this ignore strategic situations, politics,
&gt; resources, timing etc.
">

I find those hard to ignore -- how does one separate strategic
situations from the kind of war being fought at a given place and
time, or separate resources from the ability to build and operate
aircraft?  Two questions in particular really can't be ignored:

1.  At any given stage of this alternate scenario, does the fight
against the U-boats go at least as well as it really did?  Huge
implication for how you Brits get supplies and parts, and whether the
fruits of your labor can realistically go anywhere but to the MTO/ETO
without huge losses en route.

2.  Is the US still able to produce  things other than airplanes the
way we did, including the ships with which to move those things  to
the war fronts, as well as warships of all kinds (including
carriers?)   Here -- especially in the context of the Pacific war --
remember all the other ships (and their cargoes) that you need if your
objective is invasion rather than mere raids and blockades.  The US
contribution to the war was not just power but unprecedented feats of
power projection.

All in all, it would have been a much different war -- not only in
conduct but perhaps in definitions of victory.  With drastically lower
US productivity *and*  the  ability to get the fruits of it forward,
separately negotiated peace with Germany and Japan, after some
rollback of their geographical progress,  might have become a
realistic alternative to complete unequivocal victory.  (Whether the
Soviets, with Klaus Fuchs having shown them the royal road to the A-
bomb's geometry, would have revisited the issue in the late 40s is
another question entirely!)

--Joe
